<article>
    <h1>Hors&#xAD;ing around in the east</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>I have al­ways had a soft spot for Gal­lop Sta­ble @ Pasir Ris Park (above, Carpark C, 61C Pasir Ris Green). Even if your chil­dren are not old enough for rides ($10 a ride), they can still feed ponies and rab­bits ($2 for a packet of feed). Kids are also wel­come to pat the ponies.</p>
    <p>A short walk away is Pasir Ris Park Play­ground (110 Pasir Ris Road). As a child, I was per­mit­ted to play only on the lower reaches of the rope pyra­mid. While my four-year-old is not quite old enough to scam­per on the ver­tigo-in­duc­ing struc­tures, there is a wide range of newer play­ground equip­ment for younger chil­dren.</p>
    <p>We stum­bled on bistro Ge­orges @ The Cove (133 Pasir Ris Road) when it started pour­ing one time we were at the park and ended up hav­ing beers with a view of ke­longs while wait­ing for our bratwurst, slid­ers and pasta.</p>
    <p>Make a reser­va­tion or opt for a late lunch or early din­ner as it gets very busy at meal­times. Its spaghetti alle von­gole (above) has not let me down so far.</p>
    <p>Be warned: It might hard to leave the park with­out one last spin through the play­ground.</p>

